Cut the @pork medallion{4} widthways into ½cm slices. Toss your pork in the @cornflour{2%bsp} with a pinch of @salt{pinch} and a few grinds of @black pepper{}.

Boil the @water{700%ml}, in a #pot{} with a pinch of salt. Once your water comes to the boil turn the heat to the lowest setting. Add the @basmati rice{350%g} and place a tight lid on the pot. Leave on the lowest heat for ~{10%minutes}, then remove from the heat for ~{10%minutes}.

> Don't peek under the lid for 20 mins or the rice won't be perfect!

Peel and grate (or use a #garlic press{} if you have one) the @garlic cloves{2}. Peel the @ginger{2%cm piece} using the edge of a #spoon{} and then finely chop or grate it. Remove the core from the @green pepper{2} and slice lengthways into ½cm slices. Peel and chop the @carrot{2} into ½cm sticks (thinner if your knife skills allow!). Finally, chop the @spring onion{3} widthways into really thin discs then separate the white and green parts.

Put a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat and add the @cashew nuts{25%g} (without any oil). Dry-fry your nuts until they have turned brown and then remove them from the pan.

> Watch your nuts like a Wimbledon line judge, as the moment your back is turned they'll burn!

Once your nuts are removed, add a splash of @oil{} to the pan and turn the heat to high. Once it's really hot, carefully lay your pork in the pan for ~{3-4%minutes}, turning once after ~{2%minutes}.

> Cook the pork in two batches if your pan is too small, as overcrowding the pan will stew your pork rather than brown it.

Once your pork is cooked through, remove it from the pan.

> The pork is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Add another splash of oil to the same pan together with your pepper and carrot. Cook for ~{4%minutes} before adding your garlic, ginger and the whites of your spring onion. Cook for ~{30%seconds} and then put your pork back in the pan.

Mix the @black bean sauce{2%tbsp} together with 1 tbsp of water per person, then add this to the pan. Heat through, then toss everything together for ~{1%minute}, before serving it with your rice, a sprinkle of nuts and the greens of your spring onion.